SIMPLE: enormity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enormity
<hw>E*nor"mi*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Enormities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>enormitas</ets>,
fr. <ets>enormis</ets> enormous: cf. F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧normit⟦eacute⟧</ets>. See <er>Enormous</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The state or quality of exceeding a measure or rule, or
of being immoderate, monstrous, or outrageous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>enormity</qex> of his learned acquisitions.</q>
<rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is enormous; especially, an exceeding
offense against order, right, or decency; an atrocious crime; flagitious
villainy; an atrocity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These clamorous <qex>enormities</qex> which are grown too big and
strong for law or shame.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enormous</ent>⟦br⟧
